
# Contributing to linux-monitoring

Thank you for considering contributing to linux-monitoring! We welcome contributions from everyone, whether it's a bug fix, new feature, or improvements to documentation.

## How to Contribute

1. **Fork the Repository**  
   Head over to the [linux-monitoring repository](https://github.com/webbestek/linux-monitoring) and fork it to your own GitHub account.

2. **Create a Feature Branch**  
   Create a new branch for your work:
   ```bash
   git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
   ```

3. **Make Your Changes**  
   - Ensure your code adheres to the project's style guidelines.
   - Write clear and concise commit messages.
   - Update or add tests as necessary.
   - If you make any significant changes, please update the documentation accordingly.

4. **Test Your Changes**  
   Test your changes locally to verify that everything works as expected and that you haven't broken any existing functionality.

5. **Submit a Pull Request**  
   Once your changes are ready:
   - Push your branch to your fork.
   - Open a pull request (PR) against the `main` branch of the [linux-monitoring repository](https://github.com/webbestek/linux-monitoring).
   - Provide a clear description of what your PR does and reference any related issues.

6. **Review Process**  
   Your pull request will be reviewed by one of the project maintainers. They may ask for clarifications or request changes before the PR can be merged.

## Reporting Issues

If you encounter bugs or have feature suggestions, please open an issue on GitHub:
- Go to the [Issues section](https://github.com/kevinwebbestek4hrens/linux-monitoring/issues).
- Provide a detailed description of the issue, including steps to reproduce it and any relevant logs or error messages.

## Licensing Contributions

By contributing to this project, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the GNU General Public License v3 (GPLv3). This ensures that the project remains open and that contributions continue to be shared under the same terms.

## Code of Conduct

We expect all contributors to follow our [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) (if applicable) to maintain a friendly and collaborative environment.

Thank you for your contributions and happy coding!
